07663nam a22018735i 9780691233307DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021949436  a97806912333077 a10.1515/97806912333072doi  a(DE-B1597)612401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPR508.C68bH37 2022 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a821.009/38236242231 aHardie, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCelestial Aspirations :bClassical Impulses in British Poetry and Art /cPhilip Hardie. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b23 color + 48 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aE. H. Gombrich Lecture Series ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Classical Antiquity -- t3. Late Sixteenth Century to the Exaltation of Newton -- t4. Milton -- t5. After Milton -- t6 Visions of Apotheosis and Glory on Painted Ceilings -- tEpilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Passages Discussed -- tGeneral Index -- tA Note on the Type0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA unique look at how classical notions of ascent and flight preoccupied early modern British writers and artistsBetween the late sixteenth century and early nineteenth century, the British imagination—poetic, political, intellectual, spiritual, and religious—displayed a pronounced fascination with images of ascent and flight to the heavens. Celestial Aspirations explores how British literature and art during that period exploited classical representations of these soaring themes, through philosophical, scientific, and poetic flights of the mind; the ascension of the disembodied soul; and the celestial glorification of the ruler.From textual reachings for the heavens in Spenser, Marlowe, Shakespeare, Donne, and Cowley, to the ceiling paintings of Rubens, Verrio, and Thornhill, Philip Hardie focuses on the ways that the history, ideologies, and aesthetics of the postclassical world received and transformed the ideas of antiquity. In England, narratives of ascent appear on the grandest scale in Milton’s Paradise Lost, an epic built around a Christian plot of falling and rising, while also being one of the most intensely classicizing works of English poetry. Examining the reception of flight up to the Romanticism of Wordsworth and Tennyson, Hardie considers the Whig sublime, as well as the works of Alexander Pope and Edward Young. Throughout, he looks at motivations both public and private for aspiring to the heavens—as a reward for political and military achievement on the one hand, and as a goal of individual intellectual and spiritual exertion on the other.Celestial Aspirations offers an intriguing look at how creative minds reworked ancient visions of time and space in the early modern era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aArt, EnglishxClassical influences. 0aEnglish poetryxClassical influences. 0aHeaven in art. 0aHeaven in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aA Mind Forever Voyaging.  aAeneid.  aAid.  aAllusion.  aAnatoly Kucherena.  aAnnotation.  aAntiqua (typeface class).  aAntonio da Correggio.  aApollonius of Rhodes.  aApostrophe.  aApotheosis.  aBa'athism.  aBiblical poetry.  aBishop of Ely.  aBugonia.  aChairman.  aChiapas.  aChristian eschatology.  aChristian mortalism.  aChristian mysticism.  aConceit.  aConstantino Brumidi.  aControversy.  aCrowdsourcing.  aDecapitation.  aDeity.  aDemagogue.  aDictatorship.  aEdition (book).  aEdmund Spenser.  aEngraving.  aEpicurus.  aEroticism.  